Preheat your #grill{} to high.

Pop a large #saucepan{} onto medium high heat (no oil).

When the pan is hot, add the @British pork mince{240%g}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and fry until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Break up with a #spoon{} as it cooks.

Once cooked, drain off any excess fat.

> The mince is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Trim and coarsely grate the @carrot{1} (no need to peel), peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the mince is browned, stir the onion and carrot into the pork. Fry, stirring often until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%385g can}.

Once the vegetables are soft, stir in the @tomato puree{30%g}, @harissa paste{50%g} and half the garlic. Lower the heat and cook gently until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @water for the lamb{200%ml} and @chicken stock paste{1%cube} to the pork mixture.

Stir in the chickpeas.

Simmer until the mixture has thickened, stirring occasionally, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, slice the @ciabatta{1} in half as if you were making a sandwich. Pop the ciabatta on a #baking tray{}.

Drizzle the @olive oil{1%tbsp} into a #small bowl{} and stir in the remaining @garlic{1%clove}(grated), season with @salt{}, and spread onto the cut side of the ciabatta.

Grill on the top shelf of your oven until the edges are golden, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the stew has simmered, add the @baby spinach{100%g} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste and season the stew with salt and pepper if necessary and add a splash of water if it's a little dry.

Share between your #bowls{}.

Finish with a drizzle of @?olive oil{} and a sprinkle of @dukkah mix{1%tsp}.

Cut the ciabatta slices into triangles and serve alongside. Enjoy!